          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Benefits</span><h2>Benefits of Recurring Deposits</h2></div>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Disciplined Monthly Savings</strong><p>RDs enforce a regular savings habit with mandatory monthly deposits. Auto-debit from your savings account ensures you never miss a payment, helping you build a substantial corpus over time without the temptation to spend.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Guaranteed Returns Like FDs</strong><p>RD interest rates are equivalent to FD rates, and the rate is locked in at the time of opening. Your returns are predictable and guaranteed — unaffected by market volatility or economic downturns.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Low Minimum Investment</strong><p>Start with as low as ₹100/month at Post Office or ₹500/month at most banks. This makes RDs accessible to students, daily wage earners, and anyone starting their savings journey with limited income.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Flexible Tenure Options</strong><p>Choose tenures from 6 months to 10 years based on your savings goal. Whether you're saving for a vacation, a down payment, or a child's school fees, there's a tenure that fits your timeline.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>DICGC Insurance Protection</strong><p>Bank RDs enjoy the same DICGC insurance coverage as FDs — up to ₹5 lakh per depositor per bank. Post Office RDs carry sovereign guarantee, providing complete capital safety.</p></div></li>
              <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Loan Against RD Available</strong><p>You can avail a loan against your RD balance (up to 90% at some banks) at rates similar to loan against FD. This provides emergency liquidity without disrupting your savings discipline.</p></div></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">How to Start</span><h2>How to Open a Recurring Deposit</h2></div>
            <div class="steps-grid">
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">1</div><h3>Choose Bank & Compare</h3><p>Compare RD rates across banks and post offices. Consider the interest rate, minimum monthly deposit, tenure options, and whether you want auto-debit from your existing savings account.</p></div>
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">2</div><h3>Set Monthly Amount</h3><p>Decide your monthly RD installment based on your savings capacity. Start small if needed — even ₹500/month at 7% for 5 years grows to ₹35,700 (₹30,000 invested + ₹5,700 interest).</p></div>
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">3</div><h3>Open Online or at Branch</h3><p>Open RD through net banking, mobile app, or visit a branch. Set up auto-debit from your savings account on a fixed date each month. KYC documents required: PAN and Aadhaar.</p></div>
              <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">4</div><h3>Save & Grow Automatically</h3><p>Your monthly installment is automatically debited and invested. Interest compounds quarterly. At maturity, the full amount (deposits + interest) is credited to your linked savings account.</p></div>
            </div>
