  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Recurring Deposits</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the difference between RD and SIP?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Both involve regular monthly investments, but the key difference is the underlying instrument. RDs invest in fixed deposits with guaranteed returns and zero risk. SIPs invest in mutual funds with market-linked returns and varying risk levels. RDs are ideal for conservative savers who want capital safety. SIPs are better for long-term wealth creation with potentially higher returns (12%–15%) but carry market risk.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What happens if I miss an RD installment?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Missing an installment attracts a small penalty (typically ₹1–₹2 per ₹100 of installment per month of default). Most banks allow you to pay the missed installment along with the penalty in the next month. If you default for more than 3–6 consecutive months, the RD may be prematurely closed. Post Office RDs allow a grace period of 1 month without penalty.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Is RD interest taxable?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, RD interest is fully taxable and added to your total income at your slab rate. TDS at 10% is deducted if the interest earned across all deposits (FD + RD) in a bank exceeds ₹40,000 (₹50,000 for senior citizens). However, RDs do not qualify for Section 80C tax deduction like 5-year tax-saving FDs do.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can I increase or decrease my monthly RD amount?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>In a standard RD, the monthly installment amount is fixed and cannot be changed. However, some banks offer "Flexi RD" or "iWish" products where you can invest variable amounts each month (above a minimum). If you need to change amounts, you'll need to close the existing RD and open a new one, or consider a Flexi RD option.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can I withdraw my RD before maturity?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, premature withdrawal is allowed at most banks, but with a penalty of 0.5%–1% on the applicable interest rate. The interest is recalculated at the rate applicable for the period the RD was actually held (minus penalty). Post Office RDs can be prematurely withdrawn after 3 years of account opening. Some banks also offer loan against RD as an alternative.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

